\pard\f0\fs28 Many cultivars have been derived from {\b 5} and related cross-fertile species. There is great diversity in their taxonomic treatment, some authors regarding the wild plants as a separate species, {\b B. sylvestris} (L.) Miller, {\i Gard. Dict.} ed. 8, no. 4 (1768), while others regard the cultivars as subspecies and varieties of 5; Lizgunova ({\i Bull. Appl. Bot. Pl.-Breed.} ({\i Leningrad}) {\b 32}: 37-70 (1959)) recognizes five separate cultivated species with numerous subspecies. Some of the cultivars occur as escapes.
